# Nx Domain Architecture Rules

This repository uses a strict domain architecture with layered libraries.

Each domain MUST follow this structure:

libs/<domain>/
  api
  data-access
  feature
  shell

Not all domains require shell.

---

## Layer Responsibilities

### api
Contains only contracts:

- interfaces
- domain models
- DTOs
- InjectionTokens

Must NOT contain:

- implementations
- Angular services
- Http calls
- business logic

---

### data-access

Contains infrastructure implementations.

Examples:

- services
- repositories
- HTTP adapters
- persistence adapters

Rules:

- MUST implement interfaces from api
- MAY depend on Angular infrastructure
- MUST NOT depend on feature

---

### feature

Contains application logic.

Examples:

- smart components
- orchestration
- use cases

Rules:

- MUST only import from api
- MUST NOT import from data-access

Services are injected via InjectionToken.

---

### shell

Responsible for composition.

Examples:

- routing
- layout
- page containers

Rules:

- MAY depend on feature
- MUST NOT contain business logic

---

## Dependency Direction

Allowed dependency flow:

api
↑
data-access
↑
feature
↑
shell

Forbidden:

feature → data-access
api → anything
data-access → feature

---

## Cross Domain Dependencies

Domains communicate ONLY through api.

Correct:

import from:
@org/user/api

Inject token:

@Inject(USER_SERVICE) userService: UserService

Forbidden:

@org/user/data-access
@org/user/feature

---

## Services

Interfaces MUST live in api.

Example:

export interface UserService {
  getUser(id: string): Observable<User>;
}

Token:

export const USER_SERVICE =
  new InjectionToken<UserService>('USER_SERVICE');

Implementation must live in data-access.

---

## Public API

Every library must export its public API through index.ts.

Example:

libs/user/api/index.ts